WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:03.240
So, hello everyone.

00:00:03.240 --> 00:00:06.400
My name is Alex, and my talk today is going to

00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:09.000
be Building Collective Intelligence to Reduce Hostility.

00:00:09.010 --> 00:00:15.190
Several weeks ago, when I applied for this talk, the

00:00:15.260 --> 00:00:19.000
topic wasn't reducing hostility, but rather reducing division.

00:00:19.010 --> 00:00:22.570
I've since pivoted on that idea a little bit because

00:00:22.570 --> 00:00:25.500
I've realized that it isn't division that we're actually

00:00:25.630 --> 00:00:25.990
out to solve.

00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:29.740
See, I grew up in the Southeastern United States

00:00:29.740 --> 00:00:34.400
, and in recent years, I've been inspired to create

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:39.740
this project because I've seen how divided my friends and family

00:00:39.740 --> 00:00:42.990
have become on lots of different topics.

00:00:43.010 --> 00:00:46.000
But the division isn't exactly the problem.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:52.000
See, it's our differences in cultures and backgrounds and experiences

00:00:52.010 --> 00:00:56.700
that makes the world really interesting and leads to a lot of

00:00:56.710 --> 00:00:58.000
innovation.

00:00:58.010 --> 00:01:01.820
It's when the discussion around those differences leads to hostility

00:01:01.820 --> 00:01:05.990
, broken or damaged relationships, or in worst case, destruction

00:01:06.070 --> 00:01:10.190
of the world, do we start to have a lot of

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:12.000
problems.

00:01:12.010 --> 00:01:16.660
Today, a lot of the conversation around those differences takes place

00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:18.000
on social media.

00:01:18.010 --> 00:01:22.070
But it's important to realize that social media was never designed

00:01:22.090 --> 00:01:24.000
for this type of discourse.

00:01:24.010 --> 00:01:28.070
It was made to connect you with your friends, share updates

00:01:28.110 --> 00:01:30.000
, and build community.

00:01:30.010 --> 00:01:31.990
Take this post for example.

00:01:32.130 --> 00:01:35.230
Someone says, "The moon is made of cheese." Now

00:01:35.230 --> 00:01:39.190
, because they posted this to any of the popular social media

00:01:39.190 --> 00:01:44.980
platforms, and they all share this same fundamental structure where your

00:01:45.020 --> 00:01:49.070
social media profile is meant to represent you and how you see

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:53.910
the world, there's the assumption that this person actually believes

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:56.000
the moon is made of cheese.

00:01:56.010 --> 00:01:59.060
Now, because they've posted this, they've also opened

00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:05.060
themselves up to personal attack from other users who believe differently than

00:02:05.210 --> 00:02:07.540
they do, saying things like you're wrong, you're

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:11.490
crazy, or in worst case, leave the platform altogether and

00:02:11.490 --> 00:02:14.990
divide because they don't want to be affiliated with the cheese

00:02:14.990 --> 00:02:16.000
moon people.

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:19.910
Now, maybe someone else comes in and tries to remedi

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:23.070
ate the conversation, saying, "You're a little bit

00:02:23.070 --> 00:02:23.990
off base here.

00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:26.440
Here's a link to go and learn more, and maybe

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:29.310
it'll help change your perspective." But there's problems with

00:02:29.330 --> 00:02:29.990
this also.

00:02:30.010 --> 00:02:33.620
Where's this person going to be the next time somebody thinks

00:02:33.620 --> 00:02:34.980
the moon is cheese?

00:02:35.010 --> 00:02:40.250
And for our most polarized topics, it takes lots of different

00:02:40.250 --> 00:02:46.000
sources to really get a consensus of the various issues.

00:02:46.010 --> 00:02:49.410
And if we can't discuss confidently if the moon is cheese

00:02:49.410 --> 00:02:52.640
or not, how are we possibly going to be able to

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:56.990
discuss more pressing issues in the world productively?

00:02:57.010 --> 00:03:01.350
It's for all these reasons that we're building ViewS

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:01.980
ift.

00:03:02.010 --> 00:03:06.980
ViewSift is this fundamentally new type of social environment.

00:03:07.010 --> 00:03:11.830
It's an evidence-based social research platform as opposed to

00:03:11.850 --> 00:03:15.000
the traditional belief-based social media.

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:18.540
And we're building it with features in mind to help with

00:03:18.550 --> 00:03:21.990
discussing polarized content without so much hostility.

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:27.570
It starts when you create your first post on ViewSift

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:28.000
.

00:03:28.010 --> 00:03:31.050
So if you think of traditional social media, there's a

00:03:31.050 --> 00:03:32.000
text box.

00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:34.920
And at the top of the text box is a prompt saying

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:37.000
something like, "What are you thinking?

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.230
What's up in your world?" or "What's your

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:44.060
post?" Different variations to say, "This is open discourse

00:03:44.210 --> 00:03:47.000
for you to share your mind and opinions on the world."

00:03:47.010 --> 00:03:49.700
But as we've learned, that's a problem because now

00:03:49.700 --> 00:03:53.000
you've opened yourself up to attacks on your beliefs.

00:03:53.010 --> 00:03:54.990
ViewSift works a little bit different.

00:03:55.010 --> 00:03:58.000
There's still the same text box when you create your post

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.730
, but the prompt at the top is a little bit different

00:04:00.730 --> 00:04:01.000
.

00:04:01.010 --> 00:04:04.000
You see, it's as finished a sentence.

00:04:04.010 --> 00:04:07.470
"I may or may not believe," and then you put

00:04:07.470 --> 00:04:07.910
in your claim.

00:04:08.010 --> 00:04:11.440
So for example, some of the posts that I always feel

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:14.990
comfortable creating is, "The moon is made of cheese."

00:04:15.010 --> 00:04:18.280
"Aliens are real." "At proto isn't

00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:23.000
decentralized." Or, "Relays are expensive to run."

00:04:23.010 --> 00:04:25.640
And I've put a little tag on the word "rel

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:28.390
ays" to let us all know that we're talking about

00:04:28.390 --> 00:04:32.000
"At proto relays." So I create the post,

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.860
"The moon is made of cheese." And you'll notice

00:04:34.860 --> 00:04:38.230
on the ViewSift site, there's a few differences

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:40.990
to traditional social media.

00:04:41.010 --> 00:04:44.600
At the top, there's a link that centralizes the

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:48.600
discourse around this claim, "The moon is made of cheese

00:04:48.690 --> 00:04:52.050
." And there's one button where you can add support for

00:04:52.050 --> 00:04:52.990
this claim.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:56.900
And it's important to realize that on this page, you

00:04:56.900 --> 00:05:04.000
only see supporting points to support the claim above.

00:05:04.010 --> 00:05:07.910
Now, I don't have any evidence supporting the moon being

00:05:07.970 --> 00:05:09.000
made of cheese.

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:11.150
And you might be thinking, obviously it isn't, so

00:05:11.150 --> 00:05:13.980
we need to take account that perspective.

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:17.990
So that's where we've introduced the sifter.

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:21.050
When you click on the sifter, it goes to the

00:05:21.050 --> 00:05:22.980
opposite perspective.

00:05:23.010 --> 00:05:26.000
In this case, the moon is not made of cheese.

00:05:26.010 --> 00:05:29.880
And on this page, you can see the supporting claims that

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:30.980
have come in.

00:05:31.010 --> 00:05:35.390
And it's important to note that all the supporting points are

00:05:35.390 --> 00:05:38.600
claims themselves, meaning that you can click on them and jump

00:05:38.690 --> 00:05:42.710
to that claim, see all the supporting reasons, and then

00:05:42.730 --> 00:05:48.000
click on the sifter to explore other viewpoints.

00:05:48.010 --> 00:05:51.660
And this gives you the great ability to stay high level and

00:05:51.680 --> 00:05:57.870
really explore different ideas and perspectives about the world without really having

00:05:57.870 --> 00:06:02.600
to dive into all the nitty gritty complex research papers

00:06:02.650 --> 00:06:02.930
.

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:06.310
But it's at this point that we're really building on

00:06:06.310 --> 00:06:09.990
the at proto research, social research ecosystem.

00:06:10.010 --> 00:06:15.530
And today, this is kind of where we're stopping with

00:06:15.530 --> 00:06:16.990
view sift.

00:06:17.010 --> 00:06:20.000
But I guess I'd say this is our checkpoint.

00:06:20.010 --> 00:06:23.350
You can sift through different views and see the reasons that

00:06:23.350 --> 00:06:26.990
people support those views to help you break out of echo chambers

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:31.000
and thought silos and explore ideas.

00:06:31.010 --> 00:06:36.300
But pretty soon, we'll be integrating with other social research

00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:41.000
apps in the app proto ecosystem, apps like margin and symbol

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.310
, to help you identify the various quotes from sources online that

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:48.990
support ideas and link them together.

00:06:49.010 --> 00:06:53.400
And for the links themselves, you can share them with your

00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:58.260
symbol social graph and add them to collections to share with the

00:06:58.260 --> 00:07:00.000
other researchers.

00:07:00.010 --> 00:07:03.610
Then, in the future, we can build on all of

00:07:03.610 --> 00:07:08.640
these pieces to really build community-backed ways to know

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:11.000
when to trust information.

00:07:11.010 --> 00:07:15.610
And for all of the great ideas that rise from this noise

00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:19.730
that we're in, we can build features to help prioritize

00:07:19.730 --> 00:07:19.990
.

00:07:20.010 --> 00:07:23.000
If all of this sounds exciting, we're going to have

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:26.190
a table upstairs in the lounge a little bit later, so

00:07:26.260 --> 00:07:30.250
we'll have a little bit of demos you can try out

00:07:30.250 --> 00:07:33.000
and ask us questions there.

00:07:33.010 --> 00:07:35.660
Thank you so much for @Science for having me to

00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:38.790
talk with you today, and I appreciate you guys for listening

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:39.000
.

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:49.000
Thanks, Alex.

00:07:49.010 --> 00:07:50.000
Any questions?

00:07:50.010 --> 00:07:51.000
Thank you.

00:07:51.010 --> 00:07:52.000
Yeah, thanks.

00:07:52.010 --> 00:07:55.000
It sounds like a really interesting platform, and I think that

00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:57.340
there's a lot of cases where this is a useful thing

00:07:57.340 --> 00:07:58.000
to have.

00:07:58.010 --> 00:08:01.000
I wanted to ask about what plans you have for moderation,

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.360
because as a platform, I feel like you have to also

00:08:04.360 --> 00:08:08.000
make decisions on what is an acceptable viewpoint, because there's

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.580
people who give crackpot science along, say, the lines

00:08:11.580 --> 00:08:13.760
of eugenics or trying to push racist things or trans

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:15.000
phobic things and stuff.

00:08:15.010 --> 00:08:18.630
And I was wondering if you thought about moderation and how you

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:21.990
might decide, because I feel like you have to decide what

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:24.000
's an acceptable thing to discuss.

00:08:24.010 --> 00:08:26.920
First, it's important to realize that with all of these

00:08:26.920 --> 00:08:30.000
technologies, we're in the very ground stages of it.

00:08:30.010 --> 00:08:33.910
So it's important that we introduce the community to each of

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:38.450
these steps to make sure that everything makes sense before we build

00:08:38.450 --> 00:08:40.000
in other features.

00:08:40.010 --> 00:08:43.000
Moderation is absolutely very important.

00:08:43.010 --> 00:08:47.700
And by leveraging this app proto type of world, we're

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:52.810
going to focus on making this claim section of the app proto

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:57.000
ecosystem as robust as possible, because there are a lot of

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.850
nuanced details to think about that we need to do for moderation

00:09:01.850 --> 00:09:02.000
.

00:09:02.010 --> 00:09:08.860
But then we can leverage other tools to really build this community

00:09:08.860 --> 00:09:12.000
based moderation atmosphere.

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:15.000
Yeah, wonderful idea and great presentation.

00:09:15.010 --> 00:09:17.180
I'm curious how you think one of the big effects of

00:09:17.180 --> 00:09:19.980
polarization, right, is a resistance to new information.

00:09:20.010 --> 00:09:24.610
And even with new information, you'll have different interpretations of

00:09:24.610 --> 00:09:26.990
the same kind of piece of evidence.

00:09:27.010 --> 00:09:29.790
I'm curious how you all are thinking about attracting users and

00:09:29.790 --> 00:09:32.580
how you imagine folks who are already polarized are going to choose

00:09:32.670 --> 00:09:35.000
to engage with ideas with which they differ.

00:09:35.030 --> 00:09:42.170
So one of the things that really hinders people from being

00:09:42.170 --> 00:09:46.320
able to open up freely and share their ideas is when they

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:52.000
're in an atmosphere where they know the second that somebody has

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.430
a disagreement with them, that it's going to be this

00:09:54.430 --> 00:09:58.190
escalation and they're going to start attacking each other over

00:09:58.190 --> 00:10:00.000
their beliefs, all the things we talked about.

00:10:00.010 --> 00:10:02.940
So the first step we think is just creating that space where

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:05.700
you don't just have to share the things that you believe

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:08.710
in, but just generally the things that you've heard are

00:10:08.710 --> 00:10:10.000
true about the world.

00:10:10.010 --> 00:10:15.150
And then we can have open discourse on that and absolutely working

00:10:15.150 --> 00:10:20.590
with the community to develop ways to improve that type of atmosphere

00:10:20.590 --> 00:10:21.000
.

00:10:21.010 --> 00:10:25.670
But then it kind of gets this foundation where we can start

00:10:25.670 --> 00:10:32.200
having more in-person collaboration experiences with people because they know

00:10:32.200 --> 00:10:35.930
it's a safe space to share a brainstorm to move away

00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:41.670
from this hostility environment and more just a general curiosity environment

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:42.000
.

00:10:42.010 --> 00:10:48.990
So, yeah, one more question.

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:50.990
This is exciting.

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:55.510
I'm curious about the formulation of putting in a claim rather

00:10:55.510 --> 00:10:57.000
than a question.

00:10:57.020 --> 00:11:02.700
And I wonder also what it might be like to have the

00:11:02.700 --> 00:11:06.050
ability to ask questions that are beyond true, true or false

00:11:06.070 --> 00:11:07.000
or yes or no.

00:11:07.020 --> 00:11:08.000
Yeah.

00:11:08.010 --> 00:11:16.520
So this is the knowledge graph or discourse graph

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:20.000
, as you guys are calling it.

00:11:20.010 --> 00:11:21.990
There's multiple layers to it.

00:11:22.010 --> 00:11:24.480
And it's important to realize that at each one of those

00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:27.790
layers, there's a lot of things to consider with like

00:11:27.830 --> 00:11:33.800
duplicate information, moderation, and helping like the signal come from

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:35.000
the noise.

00:11:35.020 --> 00:11:41.480
And so if you think of like, you know, most

00:11:41.630 --> 00:11:46.360
things you could say, like, should we X and you

00:11:46.360 --> 00:11:48.000
could say that as a question.

00:11:48.010 --> 00:11:51.070
But then I could also say just we should X and just

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:52.980
put it out as a statement.

00:11:53.010 --> 00:11:57.380
So there's what we're doing with this claim section is

00:11:57.380 --> 00:12:01.990
focusing on the statements and getting those right.

00:12:02.010 --> 00:12:05.990
And then once we know that the community is good with that

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:10.990
part of the social graph, then we can start building questions

00:12:10.990 --> 00:12:14.090
into the mix and start to like have those questions linked to

00:12:14.090 --> 00:12:15.000
all the other claims.

00:12:15.010 --> 00:12:18.240
It's really kind of multiple levels that we're building out

00:12:18.240 --> 00:12:21.350
, not that we're trying to exclude questions from the mix

00:12:21.350 --> 00:12:22.000
entirely.

00:12:22.010 --> 00:12:23.000
Thank you very much.

00:12:23.010 --> 00:12:24.000
Thanks, Alex.

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:25.990
.
